@tmc it is indeed concern of the client (the plugin calling the lang server) to pass a config file to the server. Every language server is designed to work with VSCode, as the language server protocol itself is a microsoft thing. Language Clients just emulate VSCode ability to communicate with language servers and they usually support a config file with the same VSCode syntax (be aware that options written in a json format have to be split, they are not dot-expanded, so:
```
{
   " pyls.plugins.whatever" = true
}
```
becomes
```
{
    "pyls": {
        "plugins": {
            "whatever": true
         }
    }
}
```
the path of such file though has to be discovered within you vim plugin. With LanguageClient-neovim specify that path explicitly is just one `let g:LanguageClient_settingsPath = ...` away. Idk about vim-lsc

