I'm unsure of the robustness of using it, but there is ```hseek``` too.  It is used internally by ```bgzf_seek``` and also by samtools reheader for CRAMs.  However it works on the internal ```hFile``` structure rather than the higher level ```htsFile``` so is sub-format specific.  There is also ```hts_useek```  defined in hts.c as:

```
int hts_useek(htsFile *fp, long uoffset, int where)
{
    if (fp->is_bgzf)
        return bgzf_useek(fp->fp.bgzf, uoffset, where);
    else
        return (hseek(fp->fp.hfile, uoffset, SEEK_SET) >= 0)? 0 : -1;
}
```

I'm afraid I'm not up to speed enough to understand all the nuances surrounding seeking and to say which ones work in which environments.  I have vague alarm bells ringing about one of these interfaces not working as people expect, but I cannot recall what that conversation was about.  However these are probably starting points to experiment with if you still need the low level interface, just check thoroughly!  Maybe @jmarshall recalls the specific details.

What is it specifically which you are trying to do?  Is this seeking in a compressed context or uncompressed one?  Are you seeking to computed new locations, or only to places you have previous been to and got an offset from a corresponding tell command?

Ultimately though, I still think the preferred interface is using iterators instead to achieve the same goal as they are definitely supported fully.

@slaweksiluk The `receive` call in wishbone_master will also delete the message data for `request_msg` used in the previous iteration. This is a convenience when you have a simple "single threaded" BFM. In your case the message is placed in a queue and its data shouldn't be deleted until it has been used on the other side of the queue. You can replace `receive` with the following and then delete the message manually when it's no longer needed.

``` vhdl
      -- receive(net, bus_handle.p_actor, request_msg);
      wait_for_message(net, bus_handle.p_actor, status);
      get_message(net, bus_handle.p_actor, request_msg);
```

where status is of `com_status_t`. You can ignore the status. It's only useful to determine a timeout if you add a timeout parameter to the `get_message` call

