Not sure, whether I understand the problem correctly. However, what I usually do is to use the a single javascript output and create the required elements via the DOM API. The javascript code has access to a div inside the output area, wrapped by jQuery and exposed as `element`. As a test, I used a simplified version of the `vega.js` code (I replaced `render` with a direct call to `vegaEmbed`). For me the following works (in jupyter notebook):

```python
source = """
require(['nbextensions/jupyter-vega/index'], function(vega) {{
  var spec = {spec};
  
  var target = document.createElement('div');
  target.className = 'vega-embed';
  
  var style = document.createElement('style');
  style.textContent = [
    '.vega-embed .error p {{',
    '  color: firebrick;',
    '  font-size: 14px;',
    '}}',
  ].join('\\n');
  
  var el = element[0];
  el.appendChild(target);
  el.appendChild(style);
  
  vega.vegaEmbed(target, spec);
}}, function (err) {{
  if (err.requireType !== 'scripterror') {{
    throw(err);
  }}
}});
"""

class ChartWrapper:
    def __init__(self, chart):
        self.chart = chart
        
    def _repr_mimebundle_(self, include=None, exclude=None):
        return {
            'application/javascript': source.format(spec=self.chart.to_json())
        }

ChartWrapper(chart)
```

If you do not need the custom styling of the errors, the simpler option would be to embed the vega chart directly into the element, i.e., 

```javascript
var spec = {spec};
vega.vegaEmbed(element[0], spec);
```

